Introduction

This project focuses on analyzing students academic performance by examining the various factors that influence it, including their background, behavior, study habits, lifestyle, and overall health. By exploring the interplay between these elements, the study aims to uncover meaningful insights into how different aspects of a students life can impact their educational outcomes. To achieve this, a range of statistical techniques were employed, such as Analysis of Variance (ANOVA), Regression Analysis, Hypothesis Testing, and Data Visualization. These methods provided a comprehensive understanding of the patterns and relationships within the data, helping to draw informed conclusions and support decision-making in educational settings.

Data Description

This is student performance and behavior data set from kaggle.com. This dataset is real data of 5,000 records collected from a private learning provider. The dataset includes 23 attributes tabulated below.

Column Name Data Type Description
Student_ID String Unique identifier for each student
First_Name String Students first name
Last_Name String Students last name
Email String Contact email (can be anonymized)
Gender Categorical Male, Female, Other
Age Integer Age of the student
Department String Students department (e.g., CS, Engineering, Business)
Attendance (%) Float Attendance percentage (0-100%)
Midterm_Score Float Midterm exam score (out of 100)
Final_Score Float Final exam score (out of 100)
Assignments_Avg Float Average score of all assignments (out of 100)
Quizzes_Avg Float Average quiz scores (out of 100)
Participation_Score Float Score based on class participation (0-10)
Projects_Score Float Project evaluation score (out of 100)
Total_Score Float Weighted sum of all grades
Grade Categorical Letter grade (A, B, C, D, F)
Study_Hours_per_Week Float Average study hours per week
Extracurricular_Activities Boolean Whether the student participates in extracurriculars (Yes/No)
Internet_Access_at_Home Boolean Does the student have access to the internet at home? (Yes/No)
Parent_Education_level Categorical Highest education level of parents (None, High School, Bachelors, Masters, PhD)
Family_Income_Level Categorical Low, Medium, High
Stress_Level (1-10) Integer Self-reported stress level (1: Low, 10: High)
Sleep_Hours_per_Night Float Average hours of sleep per night

Littles Missing Completely at Random (MCAR) Test

na.test(data=Data)
## Warning: Cases with missing on all variables were removed from the analysis: NA

##  Little's MCAR Test
## 
##      n nIncomp nPattern   chi2  df  pval 
##   5000    1770        8 164.08 149 0.188

The p-vallue is greater than alpha This suggests that missing values are likely MCAR (Missing Completely at Random). There is no strong evidence that missingness depends on observed or unobserved data. The missing rows consist of 35.4% of the total records of 5,0000 hence imputation method is recommended.

#Computing missing values for numeric variables
Data$Attendance_Percent[is.na(Data$Attendance_Percent)] = mean(Data$Attendance_Percent, na.rm = TRUE)

Data$Assignments_Avg[is.na(Data$Assignments_Avg)] = mean(Data$Assignments_Avg, na.rm = TRUE)

For numeric varibles, mean approach was used to find the missing values. Multiple Imputation (Gold Standard) specifically proportional odds model (polr) was used on categorical(ordinal) variable to keep the ordering meaningful.

\(H_1\) The data in variable \(i\) are not normally distributed.

Distribution and Distribution Fitting of Total Score

ggplot(Data, aes(x = Total_Score)) +
  geom_density(fill = "skyblue", alpha = 1) +
  labs(title = "Density Plot of Total Score", x = "Total Score", y = "Density")

# Fitting the distributions
fit_lognorm = fitdist(Data$Total_Score, "lnorm")
fit_gamma = fitdist(Data$Total_Score, "gamma")
fit_weibull = fitdist(Data$Total_Score, "weibull")
fit_unif = list(min = min(Data$Total_Score), max = max(Data$Total_Score))

x_vals = seq(min(Data$Total_Score), max(Data$Total_Score), length.out = 100)


densities = data.frame( 
  x = x_vals,
  LogNormal = dlnorm(x_vals, fit_lognorm$estimate["meanlog"], fit_lognorm$estimate["sdlog"]),
  Gamma = dgamma(x_vals, fit_gamma$estimate["shape"], fit_gamma$estimate["rate"]),
  Weibull = dweibull(x_vals, fit_weibull$estimate["shape"], fit_weibull$estimate["scale"]),
  Uniform = dunif(x_vals, min = fit_unif$min, max = fit_unif$max)
)


densities_long = melt(densities, id.vars = "x", variable.name = "Distribution", value.name = "Density")


ggplot() +
  geom_histogram(aes(x = Data$Total_Score, y = after_stat(density)), bins = 20, fill = "gray80", color = "black") +
  geom_line(data = densities_long, aes(x = x, y = Density, color = Distribution), linewidth = 1.2) +
  labs(title = "Comparison of Fitted Distributions",
       x = "Scores", y = "Density") +
  theme_minimal() +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("LogNormal" = "blue", "Gamma" = "green", "Weibull" = "red", "Uniform" = "pink"))

#Kolmogorov Smirnov test for distribution fit
ks.test(Data$Total_Score, "punif", min = fit_unif$min, max = fit_unif$max)
## Warning in ks.test.default(Data$Total_Score, "punif", min = fit_unif$min, : ties should not be present for the one-sample Kolmogorov-Smirnov test

## 
##  Asymptotic one-sample Kolmogorov-Smirnov test
## 
## data:  Data$Total_Score
## D = 0.0091128, p-value = 0.8007
## alternative hypothesis: two-sided

The density curve is almost flat across the range from around 50 to 100 suggesting that total scores are uniformly distributed in that range.Students are almost equally distributed across a wide range of scores.
From further analysis, both visual and goodness of fit test confirms that the total score fit well with a uniform distribution. There is sharp drops at the both ends indicating that few students had scores around 50 and 100 as compared to scores between this range. The distribution shows some kind of balance assessment or randomness of the score.

Hypothesis Testing

Test for association between students grade and access to internet. Significant level of 5%.

\(H_0:\) Student grade is independent on internet accessibility at home

\(H_1:\) Student grade is dependent on internet accessibility at home

Contingency1=table(Data$Grade, Data$Internet_Access_at_Home)
Contingency1
##    
##       No  Yes
##   A  154 1341
##   B  109  869
##   C   79  715
##   D   84  805
##   F   89  755
chisq.test(Contingency1)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  Contingency1
## X-squared = 1.6137, df = 4, p-value = 0.8063

We fail to reject the null hypothesis since p-value is greater than the significant level. The accessibility to internet at home does not have any impact on the students grade.

Testing for the difference in average total score for male and female students. Significant level of 5%

\(H_0:\) The average total score of males and females are equal

\(H_1:\) The average total score of males and females are not equal

t.test(Data$Total_Score ~ Data$Gender, conf.level = 0.95, mu=0,  alternative = "two.sided")
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  Data$Total_Score by Data$Gender
## t = 0.69268, df = 4992.1, p-value = 0.4885
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group Female and group Male is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.5164154  1.0807335
## sample estimates:
## mean in group Female   mean in group Male 
##             75.26576             74.98360

The average total score of female students is the same as the average total score of male students. The p-value is greater than the 5% significant level hence we reject the null hypothesis.

ANOVA

Test the effect of gender, department and their interaction on total score at 5% significant level.

\(H_0:\) The mean total score is the same for both gender.
\(H_1:\) The mean total score is different for both.

\(H_0:\) The mean total score is the same for all departments.
\(H_1:\) The mean total score is different for at least one pair.

\(H_0:\) There is no interaction effect of gender and department on total score.
\(H_1:\) There is interaction effect of gender and department on total score. 

ggplot(Data, aes(x = interaction(Gender, Department), y = Total_Score, 
       fill = interaction(Gender, Department))) +
  geom_boxplot(show.legend = FALSE) +  
  scale_fill_manual(values = rep(c("pink", "lightblue"), times = 4)) +  
  labs(
    x = "Gender and Department", 
    y = "Total Score",
    title = "Total Score of Students by Gender and Department"
  ) +
  scale_x_discrete(labels = c("M-B", "F-B", "M-C", "F-C", "M-E", "F-E", "M-M","F-M")) +
  theme(axis.text = element_text(color = "black")           
  )

Model1=lm(Total_Score~Gender+Department+Gender:Department, data = Data)
summary.aov(Model1)
##                     Df  Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)

## Department           3     658  219.47   1.059  0.365
## Gender:Department    3     828  275.90   1.331  0.262

From the ANOVA table, there are larger p-values compared to the significant level for gender, department and their interaction , hence the null hypotheses is rejected at each case. This means there is no effect of gender, department and their interaction on the total score a student obtains.

Model

Model 1

Total Score = 75.86 - 0.17 \(\times\) Participation Score - 0.83 \(\times\) Family Income Level.L.- 0.21 \(\times\) Family Income Level.Q

In this model, the Total Score a student receives is slightly influenced by their participation and family income level. On average, students who participate more tend to have slightly lower scores, each additional point in participation is linked to a small drop in their Total Score. Similarly, as family income increases, theres a slight downward trend in scores, suggesting that students from higher-income families tend to score a bit lower. Theres also a small curve in the income effect, but its not strong enough to be meaningful. Overall, these effects are statistically noticeable but quite small.

A p-value of 0.0153 indicates that there is a statistically significant but weak explanatory power, with a low probability (1.53%) that this result is due to random chance. The model has adjusted R squared of 0.1485% indicating a very poor model. 0.2% of variability in total score is explained by the model leaving 99.8% unexplained. The model accounts for a very small portion of the changes observed in the outcome variable.

Regression Diagnosis on Model 1

#QQPlot

ggplot() +  aes(sample = residuals(stepwise_model1)) +

The plot is a clear indication that the residuals are not normally distributed. The points do not lie on the line.

## No Studentized residuals with Bonferroni p < 0.05

## 317 -1.814335           0.069686           NA

From the plot, no residual point is seen above the top cutoff or below the down cutoff hence no outlier detected in the residual.Again, from the outlier test, after applying the Bonferroni correction for multiple comparisons, none of the observations have residuals that are statistically significant outliers at the 0.05 level. The observation with the largest absolute Studentized residual is identified (in this case, observation 317 with a value of -1.814335). The unadjusted p-value for this residual is 0.069686, which is above the typical significance threshold of 0.05. Therefore, even before adjustment, this observation isnt considered a significant outlier.

\(H_0\): Homoskedasticity (constant variance of residuals).

\(H_1\): Heteroskedasticity (non-constant variance of the residuals).

Logistic Regression on Internet Access Classification
A regression to classify a student to whether they have access to internet at home or not.

#Logistics Regression 
Data$Internet_Access_at_Home = ifelse(Data$Internet_Access_at_Home == "Yes", 1, 0)

Data$Grade=factor(Data$Grade,  levels = c("A","B","C","D","F"), ordered = TRUE )
Data$Stress_Level=factor(Data$Stress_Level, levels = 1:10, ordered = TRUE)
Data$Family_Income_Level=factor(Data$Family_Income_Level, levels = c("Low", "Medium","High"), ordered= TRUE)
Data$Gender=factor(Data$Gender)
Data$Parent_Education_Level=factor(Data$Parent_Education_Level,  levels = c("None","High School","Bachelor's","Master's","PhD"), ordered = TRUE )
Data$Extracurricular_Activities=factor(Data$Extracurricular_Activities)



# Fit logistic model 
Logistic_Model = glm(
  Internet_Access_at_Home ~ Sleep_Hours_per_Night + Participation_Score + 
  Parent_Education_Level + Family_Income_Level + Extracurricular_Activities + 
  Stress_Level + Projects_Score + Gender + Age + Study_Hours_per_Week + 
  Total_Score + Attendance_Percent + Quizzes_Avg + Assignments_Avg + 
  Midterm_Score + Final_Score, 
  data = Data, 
  family = "binomial"
)

# Predict probabilities
predicted_probs = predict(Logistic_Model, type = "response")

# ROC analysis
roc_object = roc(
  Data$Internet_Access_at_Home, 
  predicted_probs, 
  levels = c(0, 1), 
  direction = "<", 
  quiet = TRUE
)

#Threshold
youden_cutoff = coords(roc_object, "best", ret = "threshold", best.method = "youden")
topleft_cutoff = coords(roc_object, "best", ret = "threshold", best.method = "closest.topleft")
cat("Youden cutoff:", youden_cutoff$threshold, "\nTop-left cutoff:", topleft_cutoff$threshold)
## Youden cutoff: 0.8959947 
## Top-left cutoff: 0.8959947
optimal_threshold = youden_cutoff$threshold
predicted_class = ifelse(predicted_probs >= optimal_threshold, 1, 0)


ggplot() + aes(x = 1-roc_object$specificities, y = roc_object$sensitivities) +
  geom_line(color = "blue", linewidth = 1) + coord_equal() +
  geom_abline(intercept = 0, slope = 1, color = "orchid") +
  labs(x = "1 - Specificity", y = "Sensitivity", title = "ROC Curve") 

conf_matrix = table(Predicted = predicted_class, Actual = Data$Internet_Access_at_Home)
rownames(conf_matrix) = c("Predicted: 0", "Predicted: 1")
colnames(conf_matrix) = c("Actual: 0", "Actual: 1")
conf_matrix
##               Actual
## Predicted      Actual: 0 Actual: 1
##   Predicted: 0       289      2022
##   Predicted: 1       226      2463
# Accuracy
mean(predicted_class == Data$Internet_Access_at_Home)
## [1] 0.5504

A stepwise model give an accuracy of about 0.50 which is lower than the accuracy of the original model of about 0.55 hence the original model becomes the final model. Though the accuracy is low but is better for classification, comparing to the linear regression model on the performance. From the confusion matrix, precision is about 90%.

Conclusion

Key Findings

From the analysis,

  1. Stress levels are not uniform among students since students have different stress levels. This variation could lead to differences in academic performance in the future.

  2. Whether or not a students has access to internet at home doe not impact their perform or the grade they obtain. Also a student participation in extracurricular activities does not affect their performance.

  3. Students background especially their family income level and the education level of their parents does not have impact on their academic performance.

  4. Students were scored differently in attendance regardless of the Grade they obtained.

  5. Performance between male and female students is statistically not significant.

  6. Student total score is uniformly distributed.

  7. With the logistic regression model, we can correctly classify whether a student has internet at home or not, with about 55% accuracy.

  8. There is no linear relationship existing between the variables, hence the regression model for performance and student engagement is very poor and not good for prediction.

Limitations

  1. There is no linear relationship existing between variables, hence performance can not be properly model using multiple linear regression for performance prediction.
  2. Finding the relation between variables in order to perform regression and ANOVA.

Recommendations

  1. In order to control psychological problems in the future, schools and instructors should think about offering individualized support, which would encourage under-engaged students to get more involved while also aiding extremely stressed students with coping mechanisms although stress level has no effect on performance.

  2. The sample size should be increased in order to determine hidden relationship.

  3. There might be a non linear relationship existing among the variable, further analysis is required for a non linear regression model.

  4. Although I tried a random forest model, its performance was poor with very low accuracy, so it was not included in the report. However, other machine learning models could still be applied to this data.

Data source: kaggle.com
